{"word":"τριχάϊκες","slug":"τριχάϊκες","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<entryFree id=\"n105386\" key=\"trixa/i+kes\" type=\"main\" opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"entryFree\"> <orth extent=\"full\" lang=\"greek\" opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"orth\">τρῐχάϊκες</orth> <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">[ᾱῑ], <gen lang=\"greek\" opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"gen\">οἱ</gen>,</foreign> <sense id=\"n105386.0\" n=\"A\" level=\"1\" opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"sense\"> <tr_ opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"tr\">the threefold people,</tr_> <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">Δωριέες,</foreign> so called from their three tribes (<etym lang=\"greek\" opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"etym\">᾽Υλλῆς, Δυμᾶνες, Πάμφυλοι</etym>), <bibl n=\"urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1:19:177\" default=\"NO\" TEIform=\"bibl\"> <author TEIform=\"author\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Od.\">Od.</a></author> <biblScope TEIform=\"biblScope\">19.177</biblScope> </bibl>; <cit TEIform=\"cit\"> <quote_ lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"quote\">πάντες δὲ τριχάϊκες καλέονται τρισσὴν οὕνεκα γαῖαν ἑκὰς πάτρης ἐδάσαντο</quote_> <bibl n=\"urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0020.tlg007:191\" default=\"NO\" TEIform=\"bibl\"> <author TEIform=\"author\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Hes.\">Hes.</a></author> <title_ TEIform=\"title\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Fr.\">Fr.</a></title_> <biblScope TEIform=\"biblScope\">191</biblScope></bibl></cit>. (<bibl default=\"NO\" TEIform=\"bibl\"> <author TEIform=\"author\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Apollon.\">Apollon.</a></author> </bibl> ap. Sch.<bibl default=\"NO\" TEIform=\"bibl\"> <author TEIform=\"author\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Od.\">Od.</a></author> </bibl> l. c. compares <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">κορυθάϊξ-ῑκος</foreign> and explains it as 'shaking the hair of their crests'; others rendered it <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">τρίλοφοι,</foreign> and others <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">ὀρχησταί</foreign>: more prob. Hesiod is right as to the sense; the first part is <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">τρίχα</foreign> (<pos opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"pos\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Adv.\">Adv.</a></pos>), the second not <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">ἑκάς</foreign> (as <bibl default=\"NO\" TEIform=\"bibl\"> <author TEIform=\"author\"><a class=\"S\" href=\"S:LSJ Hes.\">Hes.</a></author> </bibl> seems to suggest) but <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">ϝῐκ-</foreign> <abbr TEIform=\"abbr\">=</abbr> Skt. <tr_ opt=\"n\" TEIform=\"tr\">viś-</tr_> 'village', cogn. with <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">ϝοῖκος;</foreign> or <foreign lang=\"greek\" TEIform=\"foreign\">ϝεικ-,</foreign> another grade of the same root.)</sense> </entryFree>"}]}